               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18450407-1026-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1026-18450407 t18450407-1026-offence-1 t18450407-1026-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1026. <persName id="def1-1026-18450407" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1026-18450407" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1026-18450407" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1026-18450407" type="surname" value="MERRYWEATHER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1026-18450407" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EDWARD MERRYWEATHER</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18450407-1026-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18450407-1026-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18450407-1026-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>was indicated for stealing 1 sixpence, the monies of <persName id="t18450407-name-1313" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1313" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1313" type="surname" value="HUDSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1313" type="given" value="FLAVIUS JOSEPHUS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18450407-1026-offence-1 t18450407-name-1313"></join>Flavius Josephus Hudson</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1314" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1314" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1314" type="surname" value="HUDSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1314" type="given" value="FLAVIUS JOSEPHUS"></interp>FLAVIUS JOSEPHUS HUDSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I ama grocer, and live in York-place, Old Kent-road—the prisoner was my shopman for six montha—the first two months he had 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and then 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he had his board—in consequence of suspicion, I opened his box with a key, on Friday, the 28th of March, and on that evening I left in my till, as usual, two sixpences, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. worth of coppers—next morning I came down, about eight o'clock—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070222"></xptr>
               <p>then found in the till 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver, and 9 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in coppers—directly after breakfast I said to the prisoner, "You must have money in your pocket, which does not belong to you; I can bring parties to prove they have laid out 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. this morning, and you have only 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to show for it" (that was besides the 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. I had left in the till the night previous)—I said, "I must see what you have in your pocket"—he said, "You are quite welcome"—he took out of his pocket one shilling, one sixpence, and 2 3/4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and laid it on the counter—he said, "You see I have no marked money here; when you mark money again, take care to mark it smaller, for I saw the money was marked yesterday"—I examined the money he laid down, and observed the sixpence was marked;—I said, "Here, then, is a sixpence marked smaller, how did you come by that?"—he made no answer—I then said, "I must see in your box"—he said, "You shall, before I go"—I said, "No, I must see at once"—he said, "You shall, if you fetch a policeman"—I fetched one, and we went up stairs together—the prisoner opened his box, and we found in it a tin box, containing 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in silver—he turned out the silver, and put the box down again—I took it up, and opened an interior box, and turned out of it eleven sovereigns—I said, "How did you come by all this money? it cannot be yours, from the low wages you have had here, and what you had prior to your coming, being out of place, this money can't belong to you"—he said, "No, part of it belongs to my brother, and part is mine"—I said, "You know very well this is not your money; this belongs to me; you might have a little money belonging to you; if you like to take the silver and copper, you may go away"—being a father, I did not wish to put the law in full force against him—he said, "No," he should not do that, and I gave him in charge—this is the marked sixpence—here is a small scratch on the nose, which my wife made, but not in my presence—I only saw it when I took it out of the till.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you made him this liberal offer, he said, "I shall not give it up, I will go to the station? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I opened his box the day before with a key from a bunch of keys we have in our possession'—the first key I tried fitted the box—I had never looked into his box before—my wife looked in after I had named the circumstance to her—I looked in on the Friday that we marked the money, and I looked in again the next morning, and 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. more had been added from about the middle of Friday—I had paid him his week's wages on Saturday, the 22nd—when I looked into his box on the Friday I saw coppers amounting to nearly 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and I saw him with a respectable suit of clothes on—that gave me suspicion, which was on my mind for a considerable time—there was a deficiency of money on the Thursday, when my wife said she had noticed him serve a great many customers—no other persons go into the shop—no person goes behind the counter but my own children—I found only one marked sixpence on the prisoner—there were two marked shillings in the till that morning, and one shilling and a sixpence not marked.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You only put two sixpences and a shilling's worth of copper into the till? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I did, but there had been two marked shillings passed by customers that morning—I found the two marked shillings in the till, and only one marked sixpence—when the prisoner told me, when I marked money again to mark it smaller, I had not said anything to him about marked money.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070223"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> It was a tin box of the prisoner's in which this money was kept? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, the gold was in another box inside the tin box—I indicted him for stealing the eleven sovereigns—I have been told the Grand Jury have thrown out that bill—I had frequently missed money—I do not apprehend it was taken in sovereigns.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1315" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1315" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1315" type="surname" value="HUDSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1315" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN HUDSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's wife. I saw the eleven sove<lb></lb>reigns and 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in the prisoner's box on the Friday afternoon, and that evening I marked two shillings and two sixpences—I gave the two shillings to Mr. Fairing ton, and the two sixpences to Mrs. Pritchard, to lay out at our shop—on this sixpence produced here is a scratch at the nose, and a piece cut out at the side, in a line with it—I know the mark, and the date of the sixpence was taken as well—I can speak to this as my own mark—I never marked any other sixpences in my life.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1316" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1316" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1316" type="surname" value="FARRINOTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1316" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM FARRINOTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a baker, and live in Windsor-place, Old Kent-road. My wife showed me two marked shillings—I sent the servant girl with them to the prosecutor's shop for some articles—I took a me<lb></lb>morandum of the date and reign of the two shillings—I received two marked sixpences from Mrs. Pritchard's sister—I put down the date and reign of them—they were marked on the top of the nose and on the edge—I sent the boy out with both the sixpences—this sixpence is one of them—it is of the year 1840—it is one that Mrs. Pritchard's sister gave me, and one I sent by the boy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Joseph Biggs.</hi> I am employed occasionally by Mr. Farrington to go on errands. On that Saturday morning, about twenty minutes to eight o'clock, he gave me two sixpences, to go to Mr. Hudson's shop, to fetch 2oz. of tea and 1 lb. of sugar—they came to 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I paid the two sixpences for them that I had from Mr. Farrington—I did not notice them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BENJAMIN</hi>—(<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 107.) I searched the prisoner's box with Mr. Hudson—I found in it eleven sovereigns, fifteen shillings, four sixpences, and a lot of coppers—I heard Mr. Hudson say to the prisoner, "There is no doubt the sovereigns belong to me; if you will give me the sovereigns, you may take the silver, and go about your business"—the prisoner said part of the money belonged to his brother—this is the box—it has been a lucifer-box, I believe—this is the marked sixpence I had of Mr. Hudson.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. MERRYWEATHER</hi>. I am the prisoner's mother. I know he had money in his possession about last June—I saw it—there were six sove<lb></lb>reigns and some silver—he was of a remarkably saving turn—I know of his having a suit of clothes nearly two years—he got them at his first place—they were left by his master for mourning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1317" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1317" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1317" type="surname" value="EVANS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1317" type="given" value="CATHARINE"></interp>CATHARINE EVANS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Waterloo-street, Walworth. I have known the prisoner three years—I saw some money in his box, where he placed his clothes, three or four months before he went to Mr. Hudson's—he had six sovereigns, besides some silver, which I did not see counted he had a black coat, black trowsera, and a blue satin waistcoat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What were the clothes the prisoner had? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He had a blue satin waistcoat for one thing—I think his coat was black, and he had a pair of Wellington boots, which appeared new—I had missed money frequently—I reckoned up the wages I had paid him, and they were about 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he has a brother in some employ—I missed 8 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in amount that morning—I knew it was the intention to lay out the whole</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070224"></xptr>
               <p>of the 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. at my shop, and I ascertained that the whole of it was laid out—Mr. Farrington has the articles put down that were bought, but the woman who bought them is not here—she was at the office, but not bound over—I attend very closely to the business of my shop, but I was not there when the 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. were laid out—it is my custom to give the prisoner the key in a morning, and he comes down and opens the shop while I am dressing.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
